metadata.name: HOWL.camera #118
metadata.description:
Created with the permission and endorsement of Allen Ginsberg's estate, enabled by theVERSEverse, this work channels Ginsberg's iconic poem HOWL through a dynamic ASCII lens.

Written by Ross Goodwin using 54 of Ginsberg's original photographs and a Markov language model of HOWL in vanilla JS. Each edition shifts from the minter's chosen photograph after 10 seconds into pure ASCII noise, eventually devolving into chaotic Markov fragments.

60% of mint and royalty proceeds will be donated to benefit victims of the recent Los Angeles fires.

https://howl.camera

metadata.name: reborn #154
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: Pianist #14
metadata.description:
Asked me: Dad, are we rich?
I said: No, we are lower middle class.
Asked: What does that mean?
I said: We don't have enough money to do anything with it and we aren't that poor either.
Our lives are interesting.
A perfect balance Between pure tragedy and pure comedy.
Continually twists and turns.
Sometimes it is sad, sometimes it is funny, and sometimes it is both..

Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: Anagram #106
metadata.description:
'Anagram' explores the collision of nature with the modern world. Organic textures are generated within geometric boundaries to create a system of unique 'letters' that are combined and rearranged form a composition. Thirty-one texture types are possible, designed to work in five environments. Uncommon 'Assimilate' versions pull from the full texture set to represent the source 'word' of the generated Anagrams.

Artwork by 3dmanatee @3d_manatee. Made with p5js and ❤️.

metadata.name: Hybrid Canvas #115
metadata.description:
Exploration between generative and post-processed / procedural work.

The canvas is created with a number of pre-curated shapes previously created with a custom generative algorithm. Those shapes are post-processed to make the geometrical background.

A secondary algorithm purely generative draws on top of this canvas.

The piece lives in its own space, where lights/shades exist and rotate around. Every minute there's a change in the angle. 24 hours for a full cycle.

Controls:
- touch the piece to increase the intensity of the light/shade
- e: hide the light/shade
- c: change the color of the light/shade
- s: save an HD png screenshot

Original piece by Ismahelio. Made with p5js. Madrid, 2022.

metadata.name: Mina #68
metadata.description:
A generative series of a-symmetric compositions.

Mina is a search for new textures created by combining 3 colors with 3 different mathematical equations.

Observe how Mina blends and creates its textures in time.

Probabilities;

- 18 color palettes.

- 2 background colors.

- 4 line placements.

- 14 different compositions, most of them have variations.


Made with p5.js

Ilgın İçözü, December 2021
@distcollective
